
=========================================================================
linkatron:  A program for building working 3D linkages -- interactively!
            Written by Paul Isaacs
=========================================================================

When playing linkatron, there are 4 important guideline:

    [1]  CREATE LINKS by clicking buttons in the button-strip 

    [2]  RED and PURPLE things move when you click-drag them. Nothing else will.

    [3]  CONNECT links by dragging axles into alignment. Once connected, 
	 the dragged axle follows the other axle.  It's shape changes
	 and a 'cotter pin' appears.

    [4]  DISCONNECT an axle by dragging the cotter pin away from the axle.

If you're anxious, just type:
linkatron
and explore. Select 'help' from the pulldown menu if you get confused.


=========================================================================
OR, you can read the stuff below. (All of this information is contained
in the linkatron help cards).
=========================================================================

General:
--------
Linkatron begins with nothing but an empty table top.  As you add new links by 
clicking buttons in the 'creation button strip,' they appear on the table top.

Each kind of link has some parts that are colored red. 
You can click-drag these to change the length of a strut,
rotation of a wheel, or even the speed of a motor.
Even the table top has adjustable parts.

Once you connect two links together, they will continue to stay connected
even as you move the other pieces in your mechanism.  If you add a motor and
push its 'on' button, the mechanism will run by itself!


To Run Linkatron:
-----------------
linkatron [-hq] [ filename(s) ]

	-h          = print the usage message
	-q          = quiet mode (Disable audio effects)
	filename(s) = Inventor file or files to read into the scene.
		      If no filename is specified, you begin with an 
		      empty scene.

Creating Links:
---------------
There is a strip of buttons above the main area of the screen.
Each button creates a different kind of link.
Click on one and a new link appears on the table top in the main area.


About Axles:
------------
All types of links contain at least on axle.
Drag an axle to change an endpoint or other point of a link.
Axles have 3 parts:  a shaft, legs, and a cotter pin.
Which parts are displayed, and what color they are, can tell you a lot:
Only RED axles can be draggeed.
Only axles with LEGS can be made to follow.
ANY AXLE may act as a 'leader' for other axles to follow.

                    DRAGGABLE(RED)   CAN FOLLOW(LEGS)   CAN LEAD (ALL) 
RED  SHAFT & LEGS    X               X                  X 
RED  SHAFT ONLY      X                                  X 
BLUE SHAFT ONLY                                         X 


Connecting/Disconnecting:
-------------------------
Connect links by dragging axles into alignment. Once connected, 
the dragged axle follows the other axle.  It's shaft and legs disappear.
and a 'cotter pin' appears.
Disconnect an axle by dragging the cotter pin away from the axle. The 
shaft and legs return.

About the Types of Links:
-------------------------
Each type of link has different axles and/or moving parts.

"Single Strut" ------ A simple strut with an axle at each end.
	             -ORIGIN AXLE has legs and can be attached to other axles.
                     -The ENDPOINT AXLE moves the opposite end.
		      It has no legs and can't connect to other axles.
		      Once dragged and let go, the endpoint will maintain the
		      same position relative to the origin.

"Double Strut" ------ Two struts connected end to end.  These two struts 
		      always remain connected.  
		     -Each end has an axle that can be moved and/or connected.  
		      When you move an end, the two sub-struts will hinge 
		      accordingly.
		     -The middle point may be dragged to change the lengths
		      of the two struts.  
		     -Note that the whole thing turns
		      red as an 'error condition' if you pull the ends too
		      far apart and the struts have to stretch.  When the
		      doubleStrut is happy again, the color returns to normal.

"Wheel" ------------  A wheel you can turn. Good for driving the motion of a
	              mechanism. 
	             -An ORIGIN AXLE moves the center of the wheel.
		     -Red SIZING SPOKES change the size of the wheel when 
		      dragged inward/outward.
		     -A BLUE EDGE axle sits at the edge of the wheel and 
		      serves as an attachment point.
		      You can't connect it to anything else, but other axles 
		      may connect to it.
                     -A RED ring surrounds the edge of the wheel. Drag it to
		      rotate the EDGE axle around the wheel's center.

"Arrow" ------------- A strut that has an origin and a given length, but it 
	              always points toward a second axle, located at the 
		      'target point'.
	             -ORIGIN AXLE may be dragged and connected.
		     -TARGET POINT axle may be dragged and connected.
		     -A red LENGTH SLIDER changes the length of the arrow.
		     -A BLUE END axle sits at the end opposite the origin.
		      You can connect other axles to this point.

"Piston" ------------ This has two pieces that slide in and out from each other
		      as the ends are moved.
		     -Two AXLES (one at each end) may be moved and connected
		      to other axles.
		     -Two red LENGTH SLIDERS change the lengths of each of the
		      two pieces.
		     -Two BLUE ATTACHMENT AXLES allow other axles to attach
		      to the other ends of the sub-pieces.

"Bell" -------------- Like a piston, except that one of the two pieces is 
		      bell shaped. When the two pieces get close, the bell
		      sound is played.
                     -A RED SLIDER controls the size and therefore the pitch
		      of the bell.

"Motor" ------------- Turning on the motor causes its shaft to rotate.
		      Attach a wheel axle to this axle, and the wheel will 
		      rotate as well.
                     -A RED BUTTON turns the motor on/off.
		     -A RED SPEED STICK changes the speed and direction of the
		      motor.

The TableTop:
-------------
This is a flat surface with a grid on it.  
Drag the red corners to change the size. 
Drag the purple edge to raise and lower the table.

Active Plane -- Moving the Current Piece Forward or Backward:
-------------------------------------------------------------
The 'Current Piece' is whichever link you touched last.
There is an 'active plane' sticking up out of the table; it always shows where 
the current piece is. Move the plane and the current piece forward and
back by dragging this button.  Make the plane taller by
dragging its top edge.

Deleting & Undeleting links:
-------------------------
You can delete a link by selecting 'DELETE' from the EDIT pulldown or 
pressing <Alt> d.
You can undelete a link by selecting 'UNDELETE' from the EDIT pulldown or 
pressing <Alt> u.
Note that linkatron remembers all the links you've deleted, so you can 
perform multiple level undo.

About linkatron's files:
------------------------
Any contraption you create with linkatron can be saved to file and read 
back in.  Note, however, that linkatron uses non-standard types of nodes
and engines, so you can't read your mechanism into other Inventor 
applications.
The FILE pulldown menu contains entries for the standard
NEW, OPEN, SAVE, and SAVE AS functions.

Sample linkages:
----------------
The samples directory contains a few pre-made mechanisms. Take a look at them
by selected OPEN from the pulldown FILE menu.
   

Custominzing the Look of the Pieces:
------------------------------------
The file linkagesResourceFile.iv defines the default geometry for each
kind of link.  You can change this file to create different looking links.
